column10: CSE 142, CSE 143, CSE 311, CSE 312, CSE 332, CSE  331, CSE 351, CSE 333, CSE 473, CSE 421, CSE 455, CSE 446, CSE 344
column34: The "start displaying buttons" action may have a bug -- I set it to display for 10 seconds but it never disappeared. I also think that letting users know that they can play around with the if/else and "create list with" would be beneficial because for a long time I thought that the list had to have at least two elements in it even though I only wanted to display one button. The video tutorial demonstrating how to wait for an action to be completed was very helpful.

column10: CSE 351, CSE 331, IB Computer Science HL
column34: annoying to figure out making lists one element

I think the part about the user doing something was really confusing because there were no variables for the user which I had to create. Additionally, there wasn't exactly a timer or a while loop that matched the puzzles which I was trying to find to fit into the puzzle. Also, there wasn't the necessary puzzle blocks for some of the tasks described which left me to have some unfinished statements that I couldn't make it complete because there weren't the necessary blocks. Hopefully you guys can add those next time so that others can complete it well.

Learning in Java does not translate well to this program so was having a hard time knowing what each block did necessarily without trying them out. Also, there were two set blocks for variables in different places that I feel like should be made into one. I was going back and forth between them a lot to see which one was the right set block.

I had problems completing the main task.
I have a solid programming experience with Java/kotlin, and some with C and C++. However, I have never ever programmed robots. So I am not at all familiar with block-based programming.

I watched the tutorial on youtube, but the video quality was very poor, so I could not distinguish the text in the video. So it was not that much helpful

I felt a frustrated in the  main task - not because I did not know well how to program the robot, but because I felt like a needed a prior training before to better understand the system.
 I was mostly using trial-error but that felt frustrating and could not complete the task after spending close to 1 hour -- I wanted to really know how the system works before completing the program. For example, a prior basic training of how to detect a button pressed.
I would include some basic examples prior jumping into the main programming task.

I strongly feel that I could solve correctly the program withing a few hours, but I think it would be more efficient of actually knowing a bit more about his kind of robot programming, and not just try things out without really knowing about the platform.

column34:
The sleep callback is buggy and never gets triggered in my example, despite sleep being initiated. There's some strange interaction with the rest of the robot code.

Other than that, my biggest issue with the study was that the interface was incredibly frustrating to use. It was too small, and couldn't be resized.

Callbacks are easy enough to work with but lead to some unnecessary design patterns. (Also, in this example, I was very tempted to only wait for the longer of two robot actions to complete since it's guaranteed to finish second.)

I wasn't provided enough information to program with this application. I didn't know if when statements could interrupt each other or not. There was no option to display something until something happens.
Would be nice to have a zoom in/out feature on the interface. Sometimes there was so much code that it was hard to see everything.

column34: This program felt very similar to MIT's scratch program with one major plus--it had a much more simplified UI.  That being said, I found it very difficult to figure out what to do and how the loops worked.  As someone who does know how to code, I quickly found myself feeling frustrated not being able to find where or how to make functions call other functions.  Especially because I know I could do this easily on my own local coding environment. As a big sister, trying desperately to get her younger sisters interested in computer science I wouldn't quite recommend this to a novice but maybe an intermediate learner because the built in support isn't good for debugging or finding why your program isn't behaving as you want. I had a really hard time debugging mine (and wasn't able to successfully do so within 50 minutes so I called it quits).  Something I would like to see would be improved functionalities that would maybe highlight the block of code your robot is executing so you can see how the functions are jumping between each other?  All in all, I appreciate the efforts and think you are all doing wonderful, important work!

column10: CSE 143, CSE 311, CSE 351, CSE 331, CSE 333, CSE 332, CSE 344
column34: Wasn't very easy to understand the system; the parallel programming part definitely needs to be explained very explicitly. Most of my actual progress was made through trial and error and it took me around 50 minutes, and I have a good deal of programming experience; I don't see how a beginner is going to be able to navigate this system first try. An more in-depth tutorial on how to do basic things (I spent 10 minutes figuring out how to display a button and still kinda fudged it since I couldn't figure out how to display it without using a list lol) would also be nice.

I think it would be helpful to have a glossary/element lookup so new users can learn how each element works without referencing the first video. I think like a "Help guide" that has basic features like "how to create a button", "how to get user input" etc. would be helpful like as a toolbar on the side.

Overall, I felt that interface was easy to use. I might be the only one facing this trouble but I was not able to find a way to integrate using buttons without using a list which seemed weird because it would be using unnecessary function to create a list for one variable.

column34: There were a lot of things that I couldn't figure out the functions on the robot to do. For example, how to display only one button or have a list of just one string. The demo was slightly helpful, but a lot of the functions weren't covered, so even if I knew the concept of what I wanted to do and how to do it, it was hard to implement because of the lack of knowledge I had of where and what things I could and could not do with this robot.

column10: Intro to CS (HTML/CSS), Intro to Python, AP Computer Science A, Advanced Projects in Java, CSE 143, CSE 351, CSE 332, CSE 331
column34: I didn't have enough time to complete all the tasks.

I didn't know how to display the text of the display block based on a certain condition rather than after a certain time because I couldn't take out the for __ sec part. There might have been something wrong with how I did my repeat while block,s but it didn't seem to stop displaying the text after I entered START. I wasn't really sure how the wait for all worked with displaying the buttons (when is it "done" displaying a button - I was guessing after it was pressed?"); I guess I did it wrong because it never left the wait for all even after I pressed one of the buttons? Sometimes there was a stack trace error when I connected the display buttons block directly to the display block. I apologize if I missed something obvious, but those parts made it confusing for me and I wasn't able to really test it to get a good solution because of those misunderstandings.
